{{outdated|date=July 2014}} {{third party|date=July 2014}} '''National Audiovisual Institute''' ({{lang-fi|Kansallinen audiovisuaalinen instituutti}} or '''''{{lang|fi|KAVI}}''''') is a governmental bureau under the Finnish [[Government of Finland|Ministry of Education]] responsible for supervising the distribution of audiovisual content (including [[video game]]s), advancing [[Media studies|media education]] in [[Finland]] and archiving audiovisual material. The agency is tasked with maintaining and developing an online [[Television content rating systems|content rating system]], training independent classifiers and supervising their operation.
The agency was formed in 2014 as a result of a merger between the National Audiovisual Archive (formerly Finnish Film Archive, established 1957) and the [[Finnish Board of Film Classification]] and its short-lived successor Centre for Media Education and Audiovisual Media (2012–2014).<ref name="National Audiovisual Institute">{{cite web|url=http://kavi.fi/fi/kansallinen-audiovisuaalinen-instituutti|title=Kansallinen audiovisuaalinen instituutti|language=Finnish|accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref>
